node.text:
In this episode, we’re headed to Queenstown, New Zealand with Megan Duncan of @touchofspice_nz, Luxury Stays and Experiences. “Queenstown is known as an outdoor playground. We’ve got everything from skiing in the winter to mountain biking in the summer—there are so many walking tracks right from your front door.” Tag along as she walks through downtown Queenstown, around the Remarkables Market, and shows off the spectacular views of the city and Lake Wakatipu from the base of Ben Lomond.

Where should we go next?

node.text:
Scenes from Woodstock. In August 1969, nearly half a million people trekked to Max Yasgur's dairy farm in Bethel, New York, to see perhaps the most legendary music festival of all time. For many, getting to the festival—nestled 40 miles southwest of the town of Woodstock—was an adventure in itself. From traffic jams and picking up hitchhikers to walking miles to the location or not making it there at all, Woodstock was just as much about the journey as it was seeing Jimi Hendrix or Jefferson Airplane perform. Everyone who ventured to or attended any part of the landmark four-day festival left with a story to tell—and a community they couldn’t forget.

We spoke with a handful of people who detailed their adventures to Woodstock in the summer of 1969—link in bio. 

📷: James M Shelley

“My itinerary in Tasmania was as loose and agreeably meandering as my thoughts in the rain forest. I entirely ignored the east coast, where most foreign visitors head, and concentrated instead on the center, south, and west. Although by Australian standards the distances I covered were not great, the terrain made travel by car relatively slow—which was perfectly all right with me. The landscape was constantly changing and frequently spectacular, from the prelapsarian lushness of the Franklin to rolling green hills that could pass for the English countryside to stark vistas with an almost Nordic ruggedness.” 

At the link in bio, go off map in Tasmania's highlands and forest lodges, where trees live for millennia, trout surf on lakes, and modernist hotels stitch together the past and future.

📷: @adam.gibson.photo

September is the unsung hero of travel months: The busiest vacation season has come and gone, places are less crowded because kids are back in school, and as a result, prices on airfare, accommodations—and even attractions—have dropped. It's the perfect time to pay a visit to locations that are usually swarming with tourists and enjoy some serious natural beauty, luxury hotels, outdoor adventures, and more than a few glasses of wine. Tap the link in bio for the best places to travel next month. 

📷: @ananewyork

Canada, our recently reopened northern neighbor, boasts an extraordinarily diverse geography, from tall Rocky Mountain peaks, to expansive flat prairie land, to seaside communities on both coasts. And with a smaller national population than that of California, alone, it's perhaps unsurprising that Canada is also full of charming small towns and friendly rural communities worth planning a trip around. For your next adventure north, tap the link in bio for some of the best small towns in Canada to explore.

📷📍: Tofino Resort and Marina by Jeremy Koreski; The Wickaninnish Inn by Michael Becker

Curious about the best countries for expats? There's a lot to consider before moving abroad: how the transfer will change your daily life and influence your family; whether the health care will meet your needs; and what it means for your emotional well-being and bank account (for starters). Recently, global financial services company HSBC released the results of its annual Expat Explorer Survey. The questions, sent to more than 22,000 expats around the world, and the resulting rankings were separated into three overarching categories, or "leagues"—Living, Aspiring, and Little Expats—and all of them were considered when compiling the overall rankings. Hit the link in bio, you’ll want to bookmark these for later.

📷: @themodernleper

America has some fantastic cities, sure—but the most beautiful towns in America offer something all their own. Whether they have over-the-top American charm (we're looking at you, Woodstock, Vermont) or proximity to some of the loveliest landscapes on earth (hello, Bar Harbor), these idylls are worth a stopover, at the very least. At the link in bio, find our picks for the 26 most beautiful towns in America.

Hanoi is a perfect microcosm for the region of Southeast Asia—timeless, graceful, and unfathomably delicious, all in a compact and (relatively) manageable city. Even as it grows increasingly sleek and luxe, it remains the most romantic city in the Far East—one every traveler needs to visit. See our full list of the 50 most beautiful cities in the world at the link in bio. How many do you still need to visit? 

📷: @dustandbone_

The world is your oyster—especially if you're a bivalve-loving traveler. 🦪 Just ask the owners of oyster farms, seafood-slinging restaurants, and seaside communities throughout the country, as they rush to accommodate rising interest in everything related to the shellfish. Oyster production on the East Coast has more than doubled over the past five to 10 years to meet growing demand. And beside the fact that these briny, salty, chewy gems are enjoyable to eat, travelers are gaining interest in how oysters get on their plates, as more people want to know where their food comes from. 

Oyster experiences, from farm tours to even state-organized trails, are cropping up as a result—and they're selling out and booking up. 🦪 Learn more at the link in bio. 

📷: @erubes1

node.text:
Planning a trip to Seattle? With its mild climate and proximity to the sea, the Pacific Northwest teems with local seafood, produce, cheeses, and wine. From fine dining to fast-casual, Seattle restaurants make the most of this rich bounty. They’re so focused on food, in fact, that dress codes and formal etiquette are almost entirely eschewed. So leave the high heels and overcoats at home, but make reservations when you can—seats at the best spots fill up fast. Use our list of the best places to eat in Seattle as a strategic first move. Link in bio.

📷: @samhorine

We love presents and cake and awkward singing waitstaff as much as the next person. But planning a grand adventure for a milestone birthday is a far more memorable way to mark another trip around the sun. Whether you're a newly minted teenager or headed into your golden years, the gift of travel never gets old. At the link in bio, find some of our favorite ways to ring in each new age, from a formative trip to Paris to a once-in-a-lifetime safari. 

📷: @mary_quincy
